               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18141026-91-person860">
                  JOHN 
                  AYRE
               <interp inst="t18141026-91-person860" type="surname" value="AYRE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18141026-91-person860" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18141026-91-person860" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 22nd of October, I left my shop about half after five o'clock, and when I returned, the prisoner was in the shop in custody, and the looking-glass by the side of him. When I went out I left the looking-glass on a chest of drawers in the shop.</p>
               <p>DAVID M'QUEEN. I am a shoe-maker; I live next door to Mr. Ayre, in Drury-lane. From information, I pursued the prisoner, and took him in Newcastle-street, with the glass.</p>
               <p>Prosecutor. It is my glass.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I had been out looking for work all day; two young chaps gave me the glass, and told me to take care of it for them. I did not know what to do with it; the witness came and took me.</p>
               <p>GUILTY, aged 20,</p>
